videos_v2.description:
What Is The Missile Effect in an MRI?

The "Missile Effect" Refers to the capability of an MRI Magnetic field to attract a ferromagnetic object into the scanner with considerable force.

Examples of ferromagnetic objects:-- Ferromagnetic metal alloys usually contain iron, nickel, or cobalt. These elements are found in most metal objects.

The "Missile Effect" can pose a significant risk to a patient in the scanner and to anyone who is in the path of the attracted object.

Metal objects can become dangerous projectiles if they are taken into the scan room!

Results of The Missile Effect:
-Delayed patient Care.
-It takes 4 days to remove the object and to re-power the scanner.
-Possible injury to patients or staff.
-Possible Damage to The MRI Scanner.

Approximate cost Due to Each "Missile Effect" Incident: $250,000.
